# Current Decisions
  - test isolation: patched _cb_sync_from_db to no-op in autouse fixture to prevent real DB leaking CB state into unit tests
  - budget guard test: placeholder with skip reason=waiting-on-phase-5 (research-budget-guard.sh ships in Phase 5)
  - Walter cron: used plain crontab (no ~/.walter/jobs/ layout existed); test_results.db present on Walter, writes there
  WHY: gnhf-style overnight loop for narrow mechanical objectives (drift cleanup, lint-to-zero, mechanical refactors) that don't warrant a phased BUILD spec; each iteration makes one committed step with automatic rollback on failure
  CONTEXT: ~/.claude/commands/ralph.md, ~/.buildrunner/scripts/ralph-loop.sh
  WHY: /spec flow gives adversarial review, /predict, /ship gated pipeline, scope-guarded self-healing — ralph has none of those. Ralph is opt-in for narrow bounded work; /spec is for real feature builds.
  CONTEXT: /ralph skill docs "When to use ralph" section
  WHY: Natural-language termination condition for open-ended runs (e.g. "tests pass and lint clean"); evaluated at gate/phase boundaries where context already exists
  CONTEXT: ~/.claude/commands/ship.md, ~/.claude/commands/autopilot.md, ~/.buildrunner/scripts/ship/ship-runner.sh (_check_stop_when), ~/.buildrunner/scripts/stop-when.sh
  WHY: Long local runs (ralph, autopilot) must keep machine awake; OS-native mechanisms (caffeinate macOS, systemd-inhibit Linux, SetThreadExecutionState Windows) avoid brittle custom solutions
  CONTEXT: ~/.buildrunner/scripts/prevent-sleep.sh
  WHY: Classification work (MET/NOT_MET/INCONCLUSIVE) per the matrix — "medium for classification/filter passes only". Opus overspend would turn a cheap checkpoint into a budget bust.
  CONTEXT: ~/.buildrunner/scripts/stop-when.sh
  WHY: Single source of truth for model/effort/thinking config — never hand-roll a new prompt prefix, or drift between ralph and autopilot will appear silently
  CONTEXT: ~/.buildrunner/scripts/ralph-loop.sh _build_prompt
  WHY: Matrix rule — codex is workflow-gated (business, sales, test only). A ralph loop that dispatched codex for "begin a new feature" would violate the pin.
  CONTEXT: ~/.buildrunner/scripts/ralph-loop.sh objective-regex guard
  WHY: Preserve BR3's gated pre-push pipeline. Ralph creates commits on ralph/* branch; final publish routes through normal gates + self-healing.
  CONTEXT: ~/.buildrunner/scripts/ralph-loop.sh (no push), /ralph skill docs
  WHY: Same contract as gnhf — prevent mixing ralph iterations with uncommitted user work; keeps rollback-on-failure atomic
  CONTEXT: ~/.buildrunner/scripts/ralph-loop.sh startup check
  WHY: BR3's /autopilot + /ship + self-healing (scope-guard, diff-cap, revert-heal) already beats gnhf on every structural axis — gated pipelines, adversarial review, parallel builder nodes, cluster dispatch. Wholesale adoption would regress Phase 1–3 of BUILD_ship-self-healing-prepush.
  CONTEXT: evaluation of https://github.com/kunchenguid/gnhf
  WHY: Stop-when must never be the thing that breaks a long run. On classifier failure, timeout, or ambiguous context → continue iterating, not halt.
  CONTEXT: ~/.buildrunner/scripts/stop-when.sh fallback paths
  WHY: Initial implementation used declare-f to carry loop body through bash -c — fragile across shells and prone to quoting bugs. Re-exec with BR3_RALPH_IN_SLEEP_GUARD sentinel is less clever but survives real use.
  CONTEXT: ~/.buildrunner/scripts/ralph-loop.sh sleep-guard wrapper
